PRINCIPLES OF ECONOMICS AND BUSINESS
MICROECONOMICS VS MACROECONOMICS
macro
Macroeconomics is the study of the economy as whole It looks
at aggregate numbers for entire countries and governments.
Thus it provides a broad perspective.
Microeconomics on the other hand is the study of small eco-
nomic units It scrutinizes individuals and their decision making
from a close perspective.
trade-
TRADE-OFFS AND OPPORTUNITY COSTS
4A
People constantly face trade-off because they have to make
choices due to scarce resources. They cannot get everything
they want so they have to pick certain things over others.
Opportunity costs describe the value of the next best alter-
natives that are given up during this decision process in order
to get something else.
COMPARATIVE ADVANTAGE
If an economic actor is better at producing multiple goods than
another actor it may still be beneficial for both of them to trade
as long as the latter faces lower opportunity costs of production
(for at least one good).
In this situation, both parties can minimize their opportunity
costs working together and primarily focusing on what they

e
In most cases, the satisfaction an individual gets from
consuming certain good or service decreases as its supply
increases.
This concept is extremely helpful because it allows to pre-
dict the quantity of good or service consumers will demand.

ECONOMIC GROWTH AND GDP
Economic growth is necessary to satisfy people's desire for an
ever increasing standard of living, redistribute wealth, and
advance new technologies. However it is a means to an end
that should not become an end itself.
Growth is measured by Gross Domestic Product (GDP), the
Time
total value of all final goods and services produced in an
economy over a set period of time.
INFLATION AND DEFLATION
Most economies experience a moderate level of inflation. That
inflation
means there is an increase in the overall price level which is
equal to decrease in purchasing power of money.
Deflation on the other hand is less common. It describes de-
deflation
crease in the overall price level i.e an increase in purchasing
power of money.

INTEREST AND INTEREST RATES
interest rate
Whenever a bank loans money to someone it will expect to
receive interest in return. This way it can be compensated for
the risk of not getting the money back.
Interest rates define how much people (or institutions) have to
pay to get a loan. Thus they have a significant impact on all
monetary transactions.
FISCAL POLICY
The government can influence the economy by adjusting its
spending and tax rates. Increased spending will usually
stimulate economic activity, whereas less spending will de-
celerate it
Thus fiscal policy is often used by the government to smoothen

economic fluctuations (i.e booms and busts)
BUSINESS CYCLES
Economies generally experience alternating periods of expan-
expansion
sion and contraction in economic activity.
business cycle is initiated by an economic boom, followed by
a recession Once the trough is reached the economy recovers
and expands again until it reaches its next peak (to start the
next business cycle).
